#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:4
msgid "Introducing turtlesim and rqt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:6
msgid ""
"**Goal:** Install and use the turtlesim package and rqt tools to prepare for "
"upcoming tutorials."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:8
msgid "**Tutorial level:** Beginner"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:10
msgid "**Time:** 15 minutes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:14
msgid "Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:17
msgid "Background"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:19
msgid ""
"Turtlesim is a lightweight simulator for learning ROS 2. It illustrates what "
"ROS 2 does at the most basic level, to give you an idea of what you will do "
"with a real robot or robot simulation later on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:22
msgid ""
"rqt is a GUI tool for ROS 2. Everything done in rqt can be done on the "
"command line, but it provides an easier, more user-friendly way to "
"manipulate ROS 2 elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:25
msgid ""
"This tutorial touches on core ROS 2 concepts, like the separation of nodes, "
"topics, and services. All of these concepts will be elaborated on in later "
"tutorials; for now, you will simply set up the tools and get a feel for them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:29
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:31
msgid ""
"The previous tutorial, :ref:`ConfigROS2`, will show you how to set up your "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:34
msgid "Tasks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:37
msgid "1 Install turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:39
msgid ""
"As always, start by sourcing your setup files in a new terminal, as "
"described in the :ref:`previous tutorial <ConfigROS2>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:41
msgid "Install the turtlesim package for your ROS 2 distro:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:45
msgid "Linux"
msgstr "Linux"

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:47
msgid ""
"sudo apt update\n"
"\n"
"sudo apt install ros-dashing-turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:53
#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:148
msgid "macOS"
msgstr "macOS"

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:55
#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:59
msgid ""
"As long as the archive you installed ROS 2 from contains the "
"``ros_tutorials`` repository, you should already have turtlesim installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:57
#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:152
msgid "Windows"
msgstr "Windows"

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:61
msgid "Check that the package installed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:63
msgid "ros2 pkg executables turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:67
msgid "The above command should return a list of turtlesim's executables:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:69
msgid ""
"turtlesim draw_square\n"
"turtlesim mimic\n"
"turtlesim turtle_teleop_key\n"
"turtlesim turtlesim_node"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:77
msgid "2 Start turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:79
msgid "To start turtlesim, enter the following command in your terminal:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:81
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtlesim_node"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:85
msgid "The simulator window should appear, with a random turtle in the center."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:89
msgid "In the terminal under the command, you will see messages from the node:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:91
msgid ""
"[INFO] [turtlesim]: Starting turtlesim with node name /turtlesim\n"
"\n"
"[INFO] [turtlesim]: Spawning turtle [turtle1] at x=[5.544445], y=[5.544445], "
"theta=[0.000000]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:97
msgid ""
"Here you can see your default turtle’s name is ``turtle1``, and the default "
"coordinates where it spawns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:100
msgid "3 Use turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:102
msgid "Open a new terminal and source ROS 2 again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:104
msgid "Now you will run a new node to control the turtle in the first node:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:106
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtle_teleop_key"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:110
msgid ""
"At this point you should have three windows open: a terminal running "
"``turtlesim_node``, a terminal running ``turtle_teleop_key`` and the "
"turtlesim window. Arrange these windows so that you can see the turtlesim "
"window, but also have the terminal running ``turtle_teleop_key`` active so "
"that you can control the turtle in turtlesim."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:113
msgid ""
"Use the arrow keys on your keyboard to control the turtle. It will move "
"around the screen, using its attached \"pen\" to draw the path it followed "
"so far."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:118
msgid ""
"Pressing an arrow key will only cause the turtle to move a short distance "
"and then stop. This is because, realistically, you wouldn’t want a robot to "
"continue carrying on an instruction if, for example, the operator lost the "
"connection to the robot."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:121
msgid ""
"You can see the nodes and their associated services, topics, and actions "
"using the ``list`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:123
msgid ""
"ros2 node list\n"
"ros2 topic list\n"
"ros2 service list\n"
"ros2 action list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:130
msgid ""
"You will learn more about these concepts in the coming tutorials. Since the "
"goal of this tutorial is only to get a general overview of turtlesim, we "
"will use rqt (a graphical user interface for ROS 2) to look at services a "
"little closer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:134
msgid "4 Install rqt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:136
msgid "Open a new terminal to install ``rqt`` and its plugins:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:140
msgid "Linux (apt 1.x/Ubuntu 18.04 and older)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:142
msgid ""
"sudo apt update\n"
"\n"
"sudo apt install ros-dashing-rqt*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:150
msgid ""
"The standard archive for installing ROS 2 on macOS contains ``rqt`` and its "
"plugins, so you should already have ``rqt`` installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:154
msgid ""
"The standard archive for installing ROS 2 on Windows contains ``rqt`` and "
"its plugins, so you should already have ``rqt`` installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:156
msgid "To run rqt:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:158
msgid "rqt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:163
msgid "5 Use rqt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:165
msgid ""
"After running rqt the first time, the window will be blank. No worries; just "
"select **Plugins** > **Services** > **Service Caller** from the menu bar at "
"the top."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:170
msgid ""
"It may take some time for rqt to locate all the plugins itself. If you click "
"on **Plugins**, but don’t see **Services** or any other options, you should "
"close rqt, enter the command ``rqt --force-discover`` in your terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:175
msgid ""
"Use the refresh button to the left of the **Service** dropdown list to "
"ensure all the services of your turtlesim node are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:177
msgid ""
"Click on the **Service** dropdown list to see turtlesim's services, and "
"select the ``/spawn`` service."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:180
msgid "5.1 Try the spawn service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:182
msgid ""
"Let’s use rqt to call the ``/spawn`` service. You can guess from its name "
"that ``/spawn`` will create another turtle in the turtlesim window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:185
msgid ""
"Give the new turtle a unique name, like ``turtle2`` by double-clicking "
"between the empty single quotes in the **Expression** column. You can see "
"that this expression corresponds to the **name** value, and is of type "
"**string**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:188
msgid ""
"Enter new coordinates for the turtle to spawn at, like ``x = 1.0`` and ``y = "
"1.0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:194
msgid ""
"If you try to spawn a new turtle with the same name as an existing turtle, "
"like your default ``turtle1``, you will get an error message in the terminal "
"running ``turtlesim_node``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:196
msgid "[ERROR] [turtlesim]: A turtle named [turtle1] already exists"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:200
msgid ""
"To spawn turtle2, you have to call the service by clicking the **Call** "
"button on the upper right side of the rqt window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:202
msgid ""
"You will see a new turtle (again with a random design) spawn at the "
"coordinates you input for **x** and **y**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:204
msgid ""
"If you refresh the service list in rqt, you will also see that now there are "
"services related to the new turtle, ``/turtle2/…``, in addition to ``/"
"turtle1/…``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:207
msgid "5.2 Try the set_pen service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:209
msgid "Now let's give turtle1 a unique pen using the ``/set_pen`` service:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:213
msgid ""
"The values for **r**, **g** and **b**, between 0 and 255, will set the color "
"of the pen turtle1 draws with, and **width** sets the thickness of the line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:215
msgid ""
"To have turtle1 draw with a distinct red line, change the value of **r** to "
"255, and the value of **width** to 5. Don't forget to call the service after "
"updating the values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:218
msgid ""
"If you return to the terminal where ``turtle_teleop_node`` is running and "
"press the arrow keys, you will see turtle1’s pen has changed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:222
msgid ""
"You've probably noticed that there's no way to move turtle2. You can "
"accomplish this by remapping turtle1's ``cmd_vel`` topic onto turtle2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:226
msgid "6 Remapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:228
msgid "In a new terminal, source ROS 2, and run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:230
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtle_teleop_key turtle1/cmd_vel:=turtle2/cmd_vel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:234
msgid ""
"Now you can move turtle2 when this terminal is active, and turtle1 when the "
"other terminal running the ``turtle_teleop_key`` is active."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:239
msgid "7 Close turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Turtlesim/Introducing-Turtlesim.rst:241
msgid ""
"To stop the simulation, you can simply close the terminal windows where you "
"ran ``turtlesim_node`` and ``turtle_teleop_key``. If you want to keep those "
"terminals open, but end the simulation, you can enter ``Ctrl + C`` in the "
"``turtlesim_node`` terminal, and ``q`` in the teleop terminal."
msgstr ""

